This repository is a Bash-based Gentoo build-testing rig (tinderbox-ng).

## Description

`tinderbox-ng` builds an immutable Gentoo baseline (latest stage3 +
SWI-Prolog + [portage-ng](https://github.com/pvdabeel/portage-ng) +
matching `kb.qlf`) and exposes it as the lower layer of an
overlayfs-backed chroot. Each experiment runs in its own session whose
writes land in an upper layer that can be discarded with one command.
Sessions live under a per-namespace mount tree so the host root is
never mutated.

The headline workflow is **side-by-side resolver comparison**: run the
same target through `portage-ng` and the traditional Gentoo `emerge` in
two fresh, identical sessions and inspect their differences. The
in-repo Python tooling then feeds those per-session logs into
plan-correctness metrics (Jaccard / Kendall-tau / Spearman / dep-aware
concordance) and forecasting tables (median/p75/max of phase byte +
wall-clock counts).

`tinderbox-ng` was extracted from the `portage-ng` repository at
commit `26069d06` and now lives standalone. The "Compatibility with
portage-ng" section in `README.md` pins the cross-repo contract.

The repo follows FHS conventions: `bin/` for the on-VM entry point,
`libexec/<name>/` for executable helpers `tinderbox-ng` invokes
internally, `share/<name>/` for read-only data, and `contrib/` for
dev-machine helpers that are NEVER deployed to the VM. Each script has
exactly one home, decided by *who runs it and why*.

- `bin/tinderbox-ng` (~3970 lines): the main orchestration script.
  All user-facing subcommands and chroot/overlay/mount-namespace logic
  live here. Dispatches via a `case` block in `main()` near the bottom.
- `libexec/tinderbox-ng/`: executable helpers `tinderbox-ng` invokes
  internally (or installs into the baseline). Not user-facing.
  - `compare-merge-emerge.py` (~1570 lines): plan-correctness analyzer
    (Jaccard, Kendall-tau, Spearman, dep-aware metrics, USE/version
    diffs). Vendored from the prolog repo (`Reports/Scripts/`) at the
    `tinderbox-ng analyze` integration. **Source of truth lives here
    now.** Do NOT edit a copy in the prolog repo.
  - `consolidate-phase-stats.py` (~340 lines): aggregates per-session
    `phase_stats.pl` files into a master forecast file portage-ng can
    load as `Knowledge/phase_stats.pl`.
  - `extract-timing.py` (~470 lines): walks compare session log dirs
    and emits a JSON report comparing portage-ng vs emerge wall-clock
    timing per pass (plan/build) plus pn/em ratios, head-to-head
    wins, and per-phase totals when `phase_stats.pl` is present.
    Reads `<log>.timing` companion files written by
    `_compare_run_pass`; falls back to log mtime/ctime delta for
    older sessions and flags those entries with `mtime_estimated:
    true`. Adapted from `prolog/Reports/Scripts/extract-timing.py`,
    which was based on the legacy graph `.merge`/`.emerge` files —
    that input layout is gone, only the tinderbox-ng compare-session
    layout is supported here.
  - `compare-matrix.sh`: parallel `compare` driver over a manifest.
    Runs on the host (NOT inside chroot). Produces
    `compare-matrix-<stamp>/results.tsv` plus per-package wrapper logs.
    Invoked by `tinderbox-ng continue`.
  - `run-matrix.sh`: `tinderbox-matrix` test runner. Installed inside
    the baseline as `/usr/local/bin/tinderbox-matrix`; supports the
    `metadata|resolver|merge|test|emptytree` tiers.
- `share/tinderbox-ng/`: pure data — templates copied into the baseline
  and manifest fixtures. Nothing executable lives here.
  - `baseline.make.conf`, `baseline.package.use`, `baseline.package.accept_keywords`, `baseline.repos.conf`:
    `/etc/portage/` config copied into the baseline at bootstrap.
  - `portage-ng-dev.in`: in-chroot launcher template (with `@NPROC@`,
    `@GENTOO_PROFILE@`, `@PORTAGE_NG_ROOT@` token substitution applied
    by `cp_template`).
  - `manifest-100.txt`, `manifest-1000.txt`: matrix manifest fixtures.
- `share/man/man8/tinderbox-ng.8`: manpage, linted clean against
  `mandoc -Tlint`. Installed on the VM at
  `/usr/local/share/man/man8/tinderbox-ng.8` (symlinked by
  `deploy-host.sh`). When you add or change a subcommand / flag /
  env var, update this file too — it's the canonical user reference.
- `contrib/`: dev-machine helpers. Never deployed to the VM
  (`deploy-host.sh`'s rsync excludes `/contrib`).
  - `deploy-host.sh` (~200 lines): one-shot host install. `rsync`s
    `bin/`, `libexec/`, `share/` onto a remote VM, symlinks the entry
    point + manpage, runs `doctor`, optionally `bootstrap` +
    `selftest`. Idempotent; safe to re-run.
  - `deploy-baseline.sh`: safe scp of a single template with `@-token`
    substitution (use this instead of raw `scp` to avoid leaving
    literal `@NPROC@` in `make.conf`).
  - `render-compare-matrix.py`: render `compare-matrix-*/results.tsv`
    to Markdown for archival under `reports/`.
  - `easy-pkgs.sh`: convenience smoke driver over a curated easy-pkg
    list.
- `reports/`: historical compare-matrix snapshots (committed as
  Markdown; raw JSON / per-package logs are not in git).


## Architecture (mental model)

The script is one big bash file (`bin/tinderbox-ng`). It is structured
as a flat dispatcher that fans out to `cmd_*` functions, plus a small
internal layer for chroot/overlay/mount-namespace plumbing.

### Lifecycle (top-level subcommands, in canonical order)

1. `doctor` — preflight prerequisites (kernel module, tools, free
   space, host overlay support). Run automatically before every
   destructive op.
2. `bootstrap` — long-running (~hours): downloads + verifies stage3,
   stages a baseline under `$TINDERBOX_ROOT/baseline/`, emerges
   `dev-lang/swi-prolog` + `sys-kernel/gentoo-sources` (sets
   `/usr/src/linux`), seeds `/opt/portage-ng/`, generates `kb.qlf`,
   freezes the baseline ro. Idempotent given `TINDERBOX_REBOOTSTRAP=1`.
3. `selftest` — runs a tiny `compare` to confirm the baseline works.
4. Maintenance retrofits: `refresh-tree`, `refresh-kb`,
   `refresh-portage-ng`, `install-ccache`, `install-kernel-sources`,
   `baseline-thaw`.
5. Session ops: `new`, `enter`, `exec`, `exit`, `reset`, `destroy`,
   `list`, `diff`.
6. Resolver ops: `portage-ng` (alias `pn`), `emerge` (alias `em`),
   `compare` (alias `cmp`), `continue` (alias `resume`).
7. Observability: `status`, `progress` (alias `monitor`),
   `analyze` (alias `analyse`), `phase-stats` (alias `phase_stats` /
   `consolidate-phase-stats`), `extract-timing` (alias `timing` /
   `extract_timing`).
8. Internal: `__ns-helper` is the re-entry point inside
   `unshare --mount --ipc --propagation=private`. Never invoked by users.

### Key invariants

- Every chroot operation runs inside an unshared mount namespace
  (`unshare --mount --ipc --propagation=private`). The script re-execs
  itself with `__ns-helper` so the mounts disappear automatically when
  the helper exits, even on `kill -9`. Session `/dev/log` is symlinked
  to `/dev/null` so shadow account-tool syslog cannot reach the host journal.
- The baseline (`/srv/tinderbox-ng/baseline/`) is the OverlayFS
  **lower layer**. After `bootstrap` it is bind-mounted ro into every
  session.
- Every session is `lower=baseline + upper=sessions/<name>/upper +
  work=sessions/<name>/work + merged=sessions/<name>/merged`. Killing
  a session is `umount -R merged && rm -rf upper work`.
- `$TINDERBOX_ROOT/shared/` (Portage tree, distfiles, ccache, binpkgs,
  stage3 cache) is bind-mounted into every session at canonical
  in-chroot paths (`/usr/portage`, `/var/cache/{distfiles,ccache,
  binpkgs}`).
- The Portage tree is **git-pinned**: `_set_tree_pin()` clones,
  fetches, and `git reset --hard`s to a specific commit. The pin is
  recorded in `$SHARED_DIR/portage-tree.commit`.

### compare/analyze/phase-stats pipeline

```
compare <pkg>                 (per-package, run in parallel for both engines)
  ├─ portage-ng.plan.log[.exit][.timing]
  ├─ portage-ng.build.log[.exit][.timing]    (--build pass, only if plan ok)
  ├─ portage-ng.target.<cp>.build.log        (salvaged target log)
  ├─ phase_stats.pl                          (salvaged from /opt/portage-ng/Knowledge/)
  ├─ emerge.plan.log[.exit][.timing]
  ├─ emerge.build.log[.exit][.timing]        (PORTAGE_LOGDIR=/var/log/portage)
  └─ emerge.target.<cp>.<pf>.log[.gz]
                                                       │
                                                       ▼
analyze --run <run>         ─►  libexec/tinderbox-ng/compare-merge-emerge.py
                                  ├─ analysis.json   (structured metrics)
                                  └─ analysis.txt    (captured stdout summary)

phase-stats --run <run>     ─►  libexec/tinderbox-ng/consolidate-phase-stats.py
                                  └─ phase_stats.pl  (master forecast file)

extract-timing --run <run>  ─►  libexec/tinderbox-ng/extract-timing.py
                                  └─ timing.json     (per-pass wall clock,
                                                      pn/em ratios, head-to-head)
```

Per-session compare logs land in
`/srv/tinderbox-ng/logs/compare-<label>-<stamp>/`. Matrix-run reports
land in `/srv/tinderbox-ng/reports/compare-matrix-<stamp>/`. All three
of `analyze`, `phase-stats` and `extract-timing` auto-detect the most
recent matrix run when invoked without `--run` / `--logdir`.

`<log>.timing` companion files are written by `_compare_run_pass`
inside `cmd_compare`. Format is key=value, one pair per line:
`started=<epoch_s>`, `ended=<epoch_s>`, `wall_time_ms=<int>`,
`rc=<int>`. They are the canonical wall-clock source for
`extract-timing`; the `mtime/ctime` fallback only fires for sessions
that predate that capture and exists purely so the report doesn't
silently lose old data.


## Compare merge vs emerge plans (compare-merge-emerge.py)

This is **the same script** documented in the portage-ng `.cursorrules`,
but the source of truth is `libexec/tinderbox-ng/compare-merge-emerge.py`
in this repo (not `Reports/Scripts/` in prolog/). The metric formulas
and JSON output schema are unchanged; only the input layout differs.

### Inputs

`compare-merge-emerge.py` expects a `--root DIR` containing pairs of
files named `<label>.merge` (portage-ng output) and `<label>.emerge`
(emerge output). `tinderbox-ng analyze` builds a transient symlink
tree to bridge tinderbox-ng's per-package log directory layout to the
analyzer's flat input format:

```
<work_dir>/
├── <label1>.merge   -> /srv/tinderbox-ng/logs/compare-<label1>-<stamp>/portage-ng.plan.log
├── <label1>.emerge  -> /srv/tinderbox-ng/logs/compare-<label1>-<stamp>/emerge.plan.log
├── <label2>.merge   -> ...
└── <label2>.emerge  -> ...
```

Pairs without both `portage-ng.plan.log` and `emerge.plan.log` are
skipped silently. `cmd_analyze` finds compare logdirs via:

- For matrix runs (`--run DIR`): each `<label>.log` wrapper file under
  the run dir contains `running both engines in parallel (logs:
  /srv/tinderbox-ng/logs/compare-<label>-<stamp>)`. That path is the
  pair root.
- For ad-hoc runs (`--logdir DIR`): walk `DIR` for
  `compare-*-<stamp>/` subdirs directly.

### Pass-throughs to the analyzer

`tinderbox-ng analyze` forwards:
- `--jobs N` — parallel workers (default `nproc/2`).
- `--md5-cache DIR` — enables dep-aware metrics (DepConc%, Viol%).
  Point at `/srv/tinderbox-ng/baseline/var/db/repos/gentoo/metadata/md5-cache`.
- `--target-regex RE` — restrict to pairs whose label matches.
- `--full-lists` — include per-pair missing/extra/use-mismatch lists
  in JSON.

### Output (default `<source>/analysis.{json,txt}`)

- `analysis.json` — full structured metrics dump.
- `analysis.txt`  — captured stdout summary (line-oriented overview).

The metric formulas (`% vs portage merge_ok` for CN / CN+V / CN+V+U
+ Order% / blockers / cycle breaks / domain assumptions) are the
canonical ones documented in the portage-ng `.cursorrules`. **Do not
duplicate those formulas here** — this repo just produces the inputs
and wraps the script.

### Parser quirks (do not regress)

- **`[binary]` lines**: emerge with `FEATURES=buildpkg` (the default
  here) prints `[binary  N    ] cat/pn-ver-...` for binpkg merges.
  The `parse_emerge` regex matches both `[ebuild]` AND `[binary]`:

  ```python
  line_re = re.compile(
      r"^\[\s*(?:ebuild|binary)\s+([A-Z])[^]]*\]\s+(\S+)(?:\s+.*)?$",
      re.IGNORECASE,
  )
  ```

- **Version normalization (`split_pn_ver`)**: emerge under
  `FEATURES=binpkg-multi-instance` prints binpkgs as
  `cat/pn-ver-<BUILD_ID>` (e.g. `app-misc/jq-1.8.1-8`,
  `dev-libs/oniguruma-6.9.10-11`). portage-ng prints just `cat/pn-ver`.
  The split function:
  1. Scans **left-to-right** for the first `-<digit>` boundary
     (canonical Gentoo PMS algorithm) — NOT right-to-left, which
     mis-attributes the trailing `-<int>` BUILD_ID to the version.
  2. After the split, strips a trailing `-<int>` (without `r` prefix)
     from the version. `-rN` revisions are kept; `-N` build_ids are
     stripped.

  Test cases that must round-trip cleanly:
  ```
  jq-1.8.1                 → ('jq', '1.8.1')
  jq-1.8.1-8               → ('jq', '1.8.1')          # build_id stripped
  oniguruma-6.9.10-r11     → ('oniguruma', '6.9.10-r11')
  oniguruma-6.9.10-r11-1   → ('oniguruma', '6.9.10-r11')
  xfce4-panel-4.18.0       → ('xfce4-panel', '4.18.0')
  1password-cli-2.27.0     → ('1password-cli', '2.27.0')
  gtk+-3.24.0              → ('gtk+', '3.24.0')
  ```


## Build-time forecasting (consolidate-phase-stats.py)

Each `compare --build` session has portage-ng emit
`Knowledge/phase_stats.pl` (one `phase_bytes/3` + `phase_seconds/3`
fact per `(Entry, Phase)`), and `_compare_salvage_phase_stats` (in
`cmd_compare`) copies it into the per-package compare logdir as
`<logdir>/phase_stats.pl` immediately after the build pass — so it
sits alongside the plan/build/target logs and never relies on the
session's upper layer surviving. Across a manifest you therefore end
up with exactly one `phase_stats.pl` per compare session, all under
`/srv/tinderbox-ng/logs/compare-<label>-<stamp>/`.

`consolidate-phase-stats.py` aggregates those per-session files into
a single master. Its three input modes match the canonical layout:

- `--run DIR` (default): matrix run dir. The wrapper looks for
  `phase_stats.pl` directly under the run, and falls back to scanning
  `$LOGS_DIR` (where the per-session compare logdirs actually live)
  when none are found there.
- `--logdir DIR`: flat container of `compare-<label>-<stamp>/`
  subdirs (e.g. `/srv/tinderbox-ng/logs/`).
- `--src DIR`: arbitrary directory tree — escape hatch for ad-hoc
  consolidation across machines, archives, etc.

In all three modes the script does the same thing internally: walk
the tree for files literally named `phase_stats.pl` and aggregate
across `(Entry, Phase)`. The "literally named" walk is an
implementation detail; the canonical input layout is one file per
compare session under that session's logdir.

### Format compatibility (do not regress)

The output **must** parse cleanly through portage-ng's
`ebuild_exec:read_phase_stats/1` (a recursive `read_term/2` loop) AND
swipl's `consult/1`. Required:

- Single-quote `Entry` (`'cat/pn-ver'`); bare-atom `Phase`; integer
  `Bytes`; 6-decimal `Seconds`. Matches `format(S, '~q', X)` from
  `ebuild_exec:save_phase_stats/0`.
- Emit `:- discontiguous phase_bytes/3, phase_seconds/3.` near the
  top so the file consults without warnings (we group by entry, not
  by predicate). The directive is silently skipped by portage-ng's
  loader (term matches neither `phase_bytes/3` nor `phase_seconds/3`).
- `%!` comment headers are fine — `read_term/2` skips them entirely.

### Aggregators

| Choice  | Use case |
|---------|----------|
| `median` (default) | Robust against cold-cache outliers. |
| `mean`   | Plain average of all observations. |
| `max`    | Worst-case envelope; useful for upper-bound progress bars. |
| `p75`    | Slightly pessimistic forecast. |
| `p90`    | Strongly pessimistic forecast. |

`--min-observations N` drops `(Entry, Phase)` buckets with fewer than
`N` samples (useful when consolidating across heterogeneous fleets).
`--exclude-glob PAT` skips matching paths during the input scan; the
output file is excluded automatically (so it's safe to run in-place).

### Default output paths

- `--run DIR` (default): `<run>/phase_stats.pl` — alongside
  `analysis.{json,txt}` in the matrix run dir.
- `--logdir DIR` / `--src DIR`: `<source>/phase_stats.pl`.

For matrix runs, `cmd_phase_stats` auto-falls back to scanning
`$LOGS_DIR` (`/srv/tinderbox-ng/logs/`) when no `phase_stats.pl` files
are found under the run dir itself, since the per-package files live
under `compare-<label>-<stamp>/`.


## Naming conventions (bash + python)

- Bash subcommand functions: `cmd_<name>()` (snake_case). Internal
  helpers: `_<name>()`. Mount-namespace helpers: `_ns_<name>()`.
- Subcommand aliases: prefer `kebab-case` as the canonical name with
  a `snake_case` alias (e.g. `refresh-tree` + `refresh_tree`,
  `phase-stats` + `phase_stats`). Both go through the same dispatcher.
- Env vars: `TINDERBOX_*` for first-class config, `STAGE3_*`,
  `PORTAGE_*`, `GENTOO_*` for upstream-shaped knobs.
- Python script names use `kebab-case.py` (`compare-merge-emerge.py`,
  `consolidate-phase-stats.py`, `render-compare-matrix.py`). Module
  identifiers inside Python use `snake_case`.
- Log file names use snake_case in the filesystem (`compare-<label>-<stamp>/portage-ng.plan.log`).


## Bash file documentation style

Every long-lived `cmd_*` function in `bin/tinderbox-ng` has a section
banner and a docstring:

```bash
# =============================================================================
# tinderbox-ng <subcommand>:
#   one-line summary
# =============================================================================
#
# Longer description: what this does, what it produces, when to call it.
# Inputs (flags), outputs (paths), pass-throughs.
#
# Edge cases / gotchas worth surfacing.

cmd_<name>() {
  ...
}
```

Section banners use `# === ... ===` for top-level chapters and
`# --- ... ---` for sub-sections within a long function (rare; we
prefer to break them into helper functions).

Comments inside function bodies should explain **why**, not narrate
**what**. Avoid obvious comments. Comments that justify a non-obvious
choice (e.g. "use `bash -c "find ... -delete"` because zsh's `nomatch`
trips up `rm -rf glob*`") are valuable and should stay.


## How to develop / test (IMPORTANT)

### Local edit-test loop

The script is bash and the analyzers are Python stdlib-only. Local
quick tests:

```sh
# Bash syntax check (no execution):
bash -n bin/tinderbox-ng
bash -n contrib/deploy-host.sh
bash -n libexec/tinderbox-ng/compare-matrix.sh
bash -n libexec/tinderbox-ng/run-matrix.sh

# Python compile-check:
python3 -m py_compile libexec/tinderbox-ng/compare-merge-emerge.py
python3 -m py_compile libexec/tinderbox-ng/consolidate-phase-stats.py
python3 -m py_compile libexec/tinderbox-ng/extract-timing.py
python3 -m py_compile contrib/render-compare-matrix.py

# Manpage lint (clean run, no warnings):
mandoc -Tlint share/man/man8/tinderbox-ng.8

# Help-text smoke for new subcommand flags:
bin/tinderbox-ng <subcmd> --help
```

But you cannot exercise the chroot / overlay / `compare` flow on
macOS — that requires a Linux host with `overlay` support, root,
and a populated baseline. Test those on the VM (see below).

### Remote (VM) edit-test loop

The canonical test target is `vm-linux.local` (a Linux VM with a
fully bootstrapped baseline at `/srv/tinderbox-ng/`). Workflow:

1. Edit on macOS.
2. Push: `contrib/deploy-host.sh root@vm-linux.local`. This rsyncs
   `bin/`, `libexec/`, `share/` to `/usr/local/share/tinderbox-ng/`,
   re-symlinks `/usr/local/sbin/tinderbox-ng` and the manpage, runs
   `doctor`.
3. Quick remote checks:
   ```sh
   ssh root@vm-linux.local tinderbox-ng <subcmd> --help
   ssh root@vm-linux.local tinderbox-ng status
   ssh root@vm-linux.local tinderbox-ng list
   ```
4. Real exercise:
   ```sh
   ssh root@vm-linux.local tinderbox-ng compare app-misc/jq
   ssh root@vm-linux.local tinderbox-ng analyze --run /srv/tinderbox-ng/reports/compare-matrix-<stamp>
   ssh root@vm-linux.local tinderbox-ng phase-stats --src /srv/tinderbox-ng/logs --out /tmp/master.pl
   ```

For ad-hoc one-off runs without re-deploying every file:

```sh
# Helper script (Python or shell): goes into libexec/tinderbox-ng/
scp libexec/tinderbox-ng/<file> root@vm-linux.local:/usr/local/share/tinderbox-ng/libexec/tinderbox-ng/<file>
ssh root@vm-linux.local 'rm -rf /usr/local/share/tinderbox-ng/libexec/tinderbox-ng/__pycache__'

# Data template/manifest: goes into share/tinderbox-ng/
scp share/tinderbox-ng/<file> root@vm-linux.local:/usr/local/share/tinderbox-ng/share/tinderbox-ng/<file>
```

### Critical: `LIBEXEC_DIR` + `SHARE_DIR` resolution

`bin/tinderbox-ng` resolves two install dirs:

- `LIBEXEC_DIR` — executable helpers (`compare-matrix.sh`,
  `compare-merge-emerge.py`, `consolidate-phase-stats.py`,
  `run-matrix.sh`).
- `SHARE_DIR` — read-only data (templates, manifests).

Resolution priority (per bucket):

1. `$TINDERBOX_LIBEXEC_DIR` / `$TINDERBOX_SHARE_DIR` (env overrides).
2. `$TINDERBOX_LIB_DIR` (legacy single-bucket override; maps to both).
3. `$SCRIPT_DIR/../libexec/tinderbox-ng` and
   `$SCRIPT_DIR/../share/tinderbox-ng` — works for both dev checkouts
   and the recommended installed layout
   (`/usr/local/share/tinderbox-ng/{bin,libexec,share}/...`).

When deploying ad-hoc copies of helpers during development, **always**
scp them to `/usr/local/share/tinderbox-ng/libexec/tinderbox-ng/` (NOT
the old `share/tinderbox-ng/` path under `/usr/local/share/...`). Use
`TINDERBOX_COMPARE_ANALYZER` / `TINDERBOX_PHASE_STATS_CONSOLIDATOR` to
override per-invocation when iterating on a single helper.

### Pycache hazards

Both Python helpers are loaded as scripts (not modules), but Python
3.12+ still produces `__pycache__/` next to the script when imported.
After updating `compare-merge-emerge.py` or `consolidate-phase-stats.py`
on the VM, `rm -rf` the matching `__pycache__/` to avoid stale
`.cpython-313.pyc` files masking your edits during smoke tests.


## Common gotchas (lessons learned)

### binpkg index visibility (Issue 3, fixed)

In matrix runs, the in-flight compare sessions consume binpkgs from
`$BINPKGS_DIR` (`/srv/tinderbox-ng/shared/binpkgs/`) and produce new
ones via `FEATURES=buildpkg`. For sibling sessions to **see** binpkgs
produced by their predecessors, two invariants must hold:

1. `_ns_baseline_mount` and `_ns_session_mount` BOTH bind-mount
   `$BINPKGS_DIR` to `$M$CHROOT_BINPKGS_PATH` (`/var/cache/binpkgs`).
2. `_patch_portage_ng_host_config` rewrites
   `Source/Config/vm-linux.local.pl` to use the in-chroot path
   (`/var/cache/binpkgs`) for `binpkg:init` AND dynamically asserts
   `config:binpkg_refresh(mtime).` (default `manual` does not pick
   up new entries until process restart).

If you see "No Packages index at /srv/tinderbox-ng/shared/binpkgs/Packages"
in `refresh-kb` output, one of the above is broken.

### gentoo-sources baseline

`bootstrap_install_kernel_sources()` emerges
`sys-kernel/gentoo-sources` into the baseline, sets
`/usr/src/linux` via `eselect kernel set 1`, and runs
`make defconfig`, `make modules_prepare`, and `make modules` when
`Module.symvers` is absent (required by `linux-mod-r1` ebuilds).
Configurable via `TINDERBOX_KERNEL_PACKAGE`. Retrofit on an existing
baseline with `tinderbox-ng install-kernel-sources`. Kernel-mod compare
targets live in `share/tinderbox-ng/manifest-kernel-modules.txt`
(split from `manifest-failures.txt`).

### `git checkout master` is fragile

`gentoo-mirror` periodically force-pushes its history. Use
`_set_tree_pin()` (which does `git fetch --depth=1 origin <pin>` then
`git reset --hard FETCH_HEAD`) instead of plain `git checkout`. The
default pin tracks `origin/HEAD`, so `_resolve_default_branch()` first
queries the remote for the symref.

### zsh `nomatch` vs `rm -rf glob*`

The deploy script and ad-hoc cleanup commands sometimes run inside
the user's interactive zsh. `rm -rf foo*` fails hard if `foo*` has no
match (`zsh: no matches found`). Wrap with
`bash -c "find ... -delete"` for portability.


## Compatibility with portage-ng

The cross-repo contract is documented in detail in `README.md`, but
the short version:

- `tinderbox-ng` clones the portage-ng repo (URL + ref) into the
  baseline at bootstrap time, then `_patch_portage_ng_host_config`
  rewrites paths in the baked-in `Source/Config/vm-linux.local.pl`
  config (binpkg paths, refresh policy) to match the in-chroot layout.
- The required portage-ng entry points are
  `Source/Application/Wrapper/portage-ng-dev` (the standalone wrapper)
  and `ebuild_exec:phase_stats_file/1` (forecasting file location).
  If those move or change shape, `tinderbox-ng` breaks.
- Knowledge artefacts are baseline-internal and not in the portage-ng
  source repo: `Knowledge/{kb.qlf, kb.raw, profile.qlf, profile.raw,
  embeddings.pl, phase_stats.pl, resume.pl}`,
  `Source/{Snapshots, Certificates, Private}/`,
  `Source/Knowledge/Sets/**/*.local`. The rsync exclude list inside
  `cmd_refresh_portage_ng` is the canonical encoding.


## Development flow

- Use a git workflow.
- Start development from clean committed state.
- Iterate locally on macOS where possible (bash syntax,
  `python3 -m py_compile`, unit tests of pure functions).
- For chroot/overlay changes, push to the test VM with
  `contrib/deploy-host.sh` and exercise with a smoke `compare`.
- After a substantive change to the compare/analyze pipeline, regen a
  small matrix run and diff `analysis.json` against the previous
  snapshot in `reports/`.
- Ask user for permission to commit. Never push to remote without
  explicit consent.

When in doubt about portage-ng-side behaviour (proof semantics,
domain assumptions, knowledge base loading), defer to the
portage-ng repository's `.cursorrules`. This file is intentionally
narrow — it covers the rig, the deploy story, and the comparison
tooling, not the resolver.
